rger baselines TRIBEv2 and linear encoders. (b) Voxel-wise correlation\n98\tgain of RABBiT over upsampled TRIBEv2 (matched cortical resolution; Sec.2). (c) ROI group-level\n99\tcorrelation averaged over held-out stories and segments. RABBiT yields the largest gains in auditory\n100\tand temporal regions, with comparable performance to TRIBEv2 in higher-order language regions.\n101\t\n102\t\n103\tprecuneus/PCC, where TRIBEv2 performs better. Outside the speech-language network, predictions\n104\tin the visual and motor regions expectedly remain near chance, due to the nature of the test stimulus.\n105\t\n106\t4.2     In-silico Analyses and Ablations Results\n107\t\n108\tLanguage Localization. RABBiT’s Intact−Degraded contrast map reproduces a lot of the canonical,\n109\tstrongly left-lateralized language response [27, 14]. Fig.3a shows the contrast map of the voxels\n110\twith q < 0.0001; intact speech is preferred in left anterior temporal cortex (t = +5.7), angular\n111\tgyrus (+6.2), middle frontal gyrus (+5.8) and superior temporal gyrus/sulcus (+2.2). Despite the\n112\tpretrained backbone being acoustic in nature, after naturalistic brain-tuning, RABBiT recovers the\n113\tspatial signature of the language network without ever being trained on a controlled localizer or any\n114\tnon-naturalistic datasets.\n115\tLearned Query Embeddings. The learned ROI queries provide a direct view into the temporal brain\n116\ttransformer. Because each query specifies the speech context an ROI attends to, their embedding\n117\tgeometry reflects the model’s cortical organization. Starting from A1 and greedily stepping to the\n118\tnearest unvisited ROI in query space (cosine similarity), we recover a coherent trajectory without\n119\tany hierarchy or spatial supervision. The resulting path progresses from primary and belt auditory\n120\tcortex through STG/STS and temporal association areas toward parietal and frontal language regions\n121\t(Fig.3b), revealing an interpretable cortical structure absent in voxel-wise ridge models.\n122\tComponent Ablations. We further perform ablations to quantify component contributions. Remov-\n123\ting brain-tuning yields the largest drop in zero-shot performance (∼ 60%; Fig.3c, p < 0.001), and\n124\t\n125\t\n126\t                                                                                                             8\n127\t\f                                                                                                                                                               left hemisphere                                        right hemisphere\n128\t                                                      Intelligible vs degraded speech\n129\t                                                                 The Queen s got a great\n130\t                                                                   sense of humour.\n131\t                                                                          (intelligible speech)\n132\t                                                                                              vs\n133\t                                                                   unintelligible speech\n134\t                                                                          (matched acoustics)\n135\t\n136\t\n137\t                                                                                                                                                                          0                                               +0.39\n138\t                                                                                                                                                                                 predicted BOLD (intact degraded)\n139\t\n140\t\n141\t                                                                      (a) Language Network: strong left fronto-temporal lateralization\n142\t\n143\t                                                                      