                                     rgroup\n156\t                                                                   STG\n157\t                                                                                              0.2\n158\tPC 2 (19.3%)\n159\t\n160\t\n161\t\n162\t\n163\t                                                                               PC 2 (20.8%)\n164\t\n165\t\n166\t\n167\t\n168\t               0.0                                                        AG                                                                                                                     0.15                                                                        0.123\n169\t                                                                                                                                                               PT\n170\t                                                                                              0.0                                                     STG\n171\t               0.2                                                                                                                                                                               0.10\n172\t                                                                                                     MFG\n173\t                                                                                              0.2 IFG\n174\t               0.4                                                                                                                         TP                                                    0.05\n175\t                                             MFG                                                                                                AG\n176\t                                                          IFG                                 0.4\n177\t                                                                                                                                                                                                 0.00\n178\t               0.6                                                                                                                                                                                         RABBiT                RABBiT              Per-Subject RABBiT no RABBiT no\n179\t                      0.6        0.4       0.2     0.0          0.2         0.4                     0.6        0.4        0.2       0.0         0.2      0.4    0.6\n180\t                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 WavLM                Full-rank Brain-tuning Transformer\n181\t                                       PC 1 (23.2%)                                                                        PC 1 (23.5%)\n182\t                              Primary auditory     Belt         STG/STS           Temporal                Parietal        Frontal         greedy walk step                                                Brackets: paired Wilcoxon (two-sided) vs RABBiT. * * * p < . 001, * * p < . 01, *p < . 05\n183\t\n184\t\n185\t                     (b) Learned hierarchy from query embeddings                                                                                                                                        (c) Ablations of model components\n186\t Figure 3: Model analysis and ablations. (a) Language network localizes reproduce the canonical\n187\t left-lateralized language areas. (b) Interpretation of ROI-query embeddings learned by TBT, revealing\n188\t a learned coarse speech-to-language progression. (c) Ablation of model components shows the\n189\t importance of TBT and brain-tuning for RABBiT’s strong zero-shot performance.\n190\t\n191\t\n192\tremoving the temporal brain transformer also significantly degrades performance (p < 0.05). In\n193\tcontrast, replacing SID with larger per-subject heads provides no significant improvement despite\n194\t∼5× more parameters, and swapping Wav2Vec2.0 for WavLM-large has negligible effect. Together,\n195\tthese results indicate that brain-tuning and ROI-level routing are essential for zero-shot prediction,\n196\twhile SID provides compact subject modeling without sacrificing performance.\n197\t\n198\t\n199\t 4.3                   Few-shot Evaluation\n200\t\n201\tWe further test whether RABBiT can improve over zero-shot prediction for a new participant using\n202\tlimited fMRI calibration data. For each participant, we freeze the speech backbone, temporal brain\n203\ttransformer, and shared SID pathway, and update only the low-rank per-ROI deviation parameters\n204\t(∼115K parameters; Sec.3.8). We compare against voxel-wise ridge regression trained on the same\n205\tcalibration data using either pretrained or brain-tuned speech features [16, 2, 23]. This is a strong\n206\tbaseline: ridge fits a full voxel-wise subject-specific readout, whereas RABBiT only learns a compact\n207\tcorrection to its zero-shot prediction. We evaluate primarily on long narrative segments (∼50 min) to\n208\tallow for increasing amounts of calibration data (see App.E.1).\n209\t RABBiT few-shot improves over zero-shot with only 5 minutes of calibration and outperforms both\n210\t ridge baselines at every tested duration from 5 to 40 minutes (Fig.4a). Similar trends hold on an\n211\t additional dataset (15 min; App.E.5). The strongest ridge variant (brain-tuned features) improves with\n212\t more data but starts below zero-shot and requires substantially more calibration to match performance.\n213\t In contrast, RABBiT begins from a strong population model and uses calibration data exclusively\n214\t to refine subject-specific deviations, yielding roughly three orders of magnitude fewer trainable\n215\t parameters than ridge while achieving better prediction.\n216\tImprovements are concentrated in specific regions. At 10 minutes, the largest gains occur in IFG,\n217\tsupramarginal gyrus, mPFC, angular gyrus, MFG/DLPFC, and precuneus/PCC (Fig.4b), reaching\n218\t30–90% relative improvement. These are the same higher-order language regions identified as most\n219\tidiosyncratic in our analysis in Sec.3.1, indicating that few-shot adaptation selectively recovers\n220\t\n221\t\n222\t                                                                                                                                                                      9\n223\t\f                                              Pretrained ridge                                          Brain-tuned ridge                 RABBiT no SID                                                                   RABBiT\n224\t                                                                                                                                              p<0.05,   p<0.01,        p<0.001                 one-sample t-test of r vs Zero-shot\n225\t                         p<0.05,    p<0.01,   p<0.001   paired two-sided t-test                                                      IFG LH\n226\t                                                                                                                                                                                              n.s.\n227\t                 0.25\n228\t                                                                                  n.s.           n.s.       n.s.        Precuneus / PCC RH                                                              n.s.\n229\t                                                                    n.s.\n230\t                                                                                                                          Supramarginal LH                                                                    n.s. n.s.\n231\t                 0.20\n232\tMean correlation r\n233\t\n234\t\n235\t\n236\t\n237\t                                                                                                                                                                                                       n.s.\n238\t                                                                                                                            mPFC (ToM) RH                                   n.s.                     n.s.\n239\t                                                                                                                                                           n.s.\n240\t                 0.15                                                                                                     Angular gyrus RH                                     n.s.\n241\t                                                                                                                                                                   n.s.\n242\t                 0.10                                                                                                      MFG / DLPFC RH                                     n.s.          n.s.\n243\t                                                                                                                                                                   n.s.\n244\t                                                                                                                                    IFG RH                           n.s.            n.s.\n245\t                 0.05                                                                                                                                      n.s. n.s.\n246\t                                                                                                                        Precuneus / PCC LH                             n.s.\n247\t\n248\t                 0.00\n249\t                        Zero-shot             5.0                   9.9           20             30         40                                -25%      +0%            +25%                   +50%             +75% +100% +125% +150%\n250\t                                                                Calibration duration (minutes)                                                                            % change in r vs Zero-shot\n251\t\n252\t                                              (a) Few-shot Calibration                                                        (b) ROI % change after 10 min of calibration\n253\t\n254\t\n255\t\n256\t\n257\t                                                                           (c) few-shot difference with zero-shot for 10 mins of calibration\n258\t  Figure 4: Few-shot calibration for new participants. (a) RABBiT few-shot performance improves\n259\t  over zero-shot with only 5 minutes of calibration data and outperforms both ridge baselines. SID is\n260\t  key to this ability. (b) Per-ROI percent change in performance relative to zero-shot with 10 minutes of\n261\t  calibration (other calibration sizes reported in App.E.5). RABBiT’s largest gains occur in higher-order\n262\t  ROIs that were most idiosyncratic in the shared–idiosyncratic diagnostic (Sec.3.1.1). (c) Difference\n263\t  between few-shot and zero-shot predictions after 10mins of calibration; results for more calibration\n264\t  sizes and other baselines can be found in App.E.5.\n265\t\n266\t\n267\t  structured individual variability. Ridge baselines do not show comparable targeted recovery at low\n268\t  data regimes, though they approach similar trends with substantially more data (App.E.5).\n269\t\n270\t\n271\t  5                      Discussion and Conclusion\n272\t\n273\t  The central insight of RABBiT is that accurate personalization in predicting language-evoked fMRI\n274\t  does not require fitting a new high-dimensional model for every participant. Instead, RABBiT\n275\t  separates prediction into a shared speech-to-brain mapping and a compact subject-specific correction\n276\t  pathway. This structure naturally supports both transfer regimes explored in this work: zero-shot pre-\n277\t  diction through the shared component, and few-shot adaptation through low-rank subject deviations.\n278\t  RABBiT bridges a gap between prior brain-tuning approaches and recent foundation-style brain\n279\t  encoders. Brain-tuning improves speech representations for fMRI prediction, but still relies\n280\t  on participant-specific voxel-wise readouts [21, 23, 31]. Foundation-style models move toward\n281\t  population-level prediction, but often depend on large backbones, subject-specific heads, or coarse\n282\t  spatial outputs [7, 5]. In contrast, RABBiT shows that a compact audio-only encoder can achieve\n283\t  highly accurate group-level prediction while supporting efficient subject adaptation from only minutes\n284\t  of calibration data. Importantly, calibration updates only the compact SID deviation pathway rather\n285\t  than relearning the full speech-to-brain mapping.\n286\t\n287\t\n288\t                                                                                                                   10\n289\t\fThe regional structure of these gains is particularly informative. Higher-order language regions both\n290\texhibit the largest inter-subject variability and benefit most from few-shot adaptation, indicating that\n291\tindividual differences are structured rather than noise-like. SID captures this structure in a compact\n292\trepresentation that can be efficiently adapted with limited data.\n293\tThe temporal brain transformer provides a complementary level of structure by learning ROI-specific\n294\ttemporal queries over the speech stream. Beyond improving prediction, these learned queries recover\n295\ta coarse progression from auditory to higher-order language regions without explicit supervision,\n296\tsuggesting a promising framework for probing cortical language hierarchies.\n297\tTogether, these results position RABBiT as a foundation model of language-evoked brain activity.\n298\tThe model predicts responses for unseen listeners without additional fMRI, adapts efficiently to new\n299\tindividuals, and exposes interpretable regional structure. More broadly, our findings suggest that\n300\teffective brain foundation models should explicitly separate shared and individual variability and\n301\tmodel how different brain regions integrate information over time.\n302\t\n303\tLimitations and Future Work. RABBiT is evaluated primarily on English naturalistic listening\n304\tand auditory/language regions. Extending the evaluation to multilingual, conversational, reading,\n305\tand multimodal settings will assess the generality of its shared and subject-specific representations.\n306\tSecond, the training cohort remains relatively small, and preliminary experiments combining datasets\n307\tdid not yield proportional gains, suggesting that scaling training across datasets may require improved\n308\thandling of inter-dataset variability. Finally, we only partially explored scaling to larger speech\n309\tbackbones; a more systematic investigation of model scaling remains a direction for future work.\n310\t\n311\t\n312\t\n313\t\n314\t                                                  11\n315\t\fReferences\n316\t [1] Hossein Adeli, Minni Sun, and Nikolaus Kriegeskorte. Transformer brain encoders explain\n317\t     human high-level visual responses. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems\n318\t     (NeurIPS), 2025. Spotlight.\n319\t [2] Richard Antonello, Aditya Vaidya, and Alexander Huth. Scaling laws for language encoding\n320\t     models in fmri. Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, 36, 2024.\n321\t [3] Alexei Baevski, Yuhao Zhou, Abdelrahman Mohamed, and Michael Auli. wav2vec 2.0:\n322\t     A framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations. Advances in Neural\n323\t     Information Processing Syst